=3DUTF-8"><title>Volume Patterns for Pyramids</title>
</head><body bgcolor=3D"white">

<center><h2>Volume Patterns for Pyramids</h2></center>

<p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

In nearly all of the important formulas for measuring objects, the=20
different dimensions appear either in the exponents or the coefficients.=20
For volumes of cones and pyramids, the dimensions show up in two different=
=20
ways.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

</p><center>
<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"5" cellpadding=3D"0" width=3D"350">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"CENTER">
<table border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"3" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td><img src=3D"https://www.math.brown.edu/tbanchof/Beyond3d/Ima=
ges/chapter2/image05.jpg" width=3D"502" height=3D"160"></td></tr>
</tbody></table></td></tr>
<tr><td><p align=3D"CENTER">
<small>The contents of three conical cups exactly fill a cylinder=20
of the same radius and height.</small></p></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</center>

<p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

</p><center>
<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"5" cellpadding=3D"0" width=3D"350">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"CENTER">
<table border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"3" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td><img src=3D"https://www.math.brown.edu/tbanchof/Beyond3d/Ima=
ges/chapter2/image06.jpg" width=3D"502" height=3D"161"></td></tr>
</tbody></table></td></tr>
<tr><td><p align=3D"CENTER">
<small>The contents of three pyramids with rectangular bases=20
exactly fill a prism of the same base and height.</small></p></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</center>

<p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

We do not know which ancient artisan first filled a cone three times from=
=20
the water in a cylinder and thereby observed that the volume of a cylinder=
=20
is three times the volume of a cone with like base and height. This=20
relationship was later recognized to hold in a wide range of figures:  a=20
prism with rectangular sides and square or triangular base has three times=
=20
the volume of a pyramid with like base and height.  Once we observe this=20
relationship, we can express it in formula:  the volume of a cylinder or=20
prism is the area of the base multiplied by the height, and the volume of a=
=20
cone or pyramid is one-third the volume of the corresponding cylinder or=20
prism.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"5" cellpadding=3D"0" width=3D"150" align=
=3D"RIGHT">
<tbody><tr><td rowspan=3D"2"></td><td align=3D"CENTER">
<table border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"3" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td><img src=3D"https://www.math.brown.edu/tbanchof/Beyond3d/Ima=
ges/chapter2/image07.jpg" width=3D"137" height=3D"270"></td></tr>
</tbody></table></td></tr>
<tr><td><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">
<small>Two congruent right triangles meet along a diagonal of a square.</sm=
all></p></td></tr>
<tr></tr>
</tbody></table>

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

The relationship between volumes of prisms and volumes of pyramids is=20
analogous to the relationship between areas of rectangles and areas of=20
triangles in the plane.  A diagonal line divides a square into two=20
congruent isosceles right triangles.  More generally, the area of a=20
rectangle is the length of the base multiplied by the height, and the area=
=20
of a triangle is one-half the length of the base multiplied by the height. =
=20
The pattern lies in the denominatior of the fraction.  If we consider a=20
four-dimensional  analogue of a pyramid, then its four-dimensional volume=
=20
should be one-fourth the volume of its three-dimensional base multiplied by=
=20
its height in a fourth direction.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

Mathematcians are not content merely to observe a pattern:  they want to=20
find an argument that shows why the same pattern will always occur.=20
Experiments with water-filled pyramids do not provide a proof of the volume=
=20
formula in three dimensions.  Fortunately we can establish this=20
relationship by decomposing a cube into three congruent pyramids. Just as a=
=20
square is decomposed into two congruent triangles which meet along a=20
diagonal line, a cube can be decomposed into three identical pieces which=
=20
meet along a diagonal of the cube. Each of the pieces is a square-based=20
pyramid, with its top point directly over one corner of the square base. It=
=20
follows that the volume of each piece is one-third the volume of the cube.=
=20
From the relationships in the second and third dimensions, the pattern is=
=20
already clear. We cannot construct a real model to illustrate the analogous=
=20
relationship in the fourth dimension, but we can still proceed to formulate=
=20
hvpotheses. We expect that a four-dimensional hypercube can be decomposed=
=20
into four congruent off-center four-dimensional pyramids meeting along the=
=20
longest diagonal of the hypercube. In general the <i>n</i>-dimensioiial=20
cube should be decomposable into <i>n</i> congruent off-center=20
<i>n</i>-dimensional pyramids, each with an (<i>n</i>-1)-dimensional cube=
=20
as its base.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

The pattern appears both in the exponents and in the denominators of the=20
formulas for area and volume of an off-center pyramid. The area of an=20
isosceles triangle with side length <i>m</i>is <i>m</i><sup>2</sup>/2. The=
=20
volume of an off-center pyramid obtained from a cube of side length=20
<i>m</i> is <i>m</i><sup>3</sup>/3. The pattern predicts that the=20
four-dimensional volume of an off-center four-dimensional pyramid obtained=
=20
from a hvpercube of side length <i>m</i> is <i>m</i><sup>4</sup>/4 . The=20
analogous formula for the n-dimensional volume of an off-center=20
n-dimensional pyramid is m<sup>n</sup>/n.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

</p><center>
<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"5" cellpadding=3D"0" width=3D"350">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"CENTER">
<table border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"3" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td><img src=3D"https://www.math.brown.edu/tbanchof/Beyond3d/Ima=
ges/chapter2/image08.jpg" width=3D"322" height=3D"170"></td></tr>
</tbody></table></td></tr>
<tr><td><p align=3D"CENTER">
<small>Three congruent pyramids meet along a diagonal of a cube.</small></p=
></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</center>

<p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

The analogy between the decomposition of the square in the plane and the=20
cube in space gave us a way to find the volume formula for an off-center=20
pyramid with a square base. We would like to prove a formula for a more=20
general class of pyramids with rectangular bases, but unfortunately the=20
analogy between a rectangular region in the plane and a rectangular prism=
=20
in space is not a perfect one. A square is divided into two congruent=20
triangles by a diagonal, and so is a rectangular region. But even though a=
=20
cube can be divided into three congruent pieces meeting along a diagonal,=
=20
it is usually not possible to decompose a rectangular prism into three=20
congruent pieces meeting along a diagonal. However, it is still possible to=
=20
divide the rectangular prism into three noncongruent pieces of equal=20
volume, and this result relies on a more sophisticated phenomenon, namely=
=20
the effect of a scale transformation along a single direction.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

</p><center>
<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"5" cellpadding=3D"0" width=3D"350">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"CENTER">
<table border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"3" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td><img src=3D"https://www.math.brown.edu/tbanchof/Beyond3d/Ima=
ges/chapter2/image09.jpg" width=3D"533" height=3D"170"></td></tr>
</tbody></table></td></tr>
<tr><td><p align=3D"CENTER">
<small>Three noncongruent pyramids with equal volume meet along a=20
diagonal of a rectangular prism.</small></p></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</center>

<p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

We can approximate the volume of a pyramid by stacking thick rectangular=20
cards parallel to the base. If we double the thickness of each card in the=
=20
stack, then the base stays the same while the height doubles and the weight=
=20
of the stack (and therefore its volume) also doubles. If we keep the width=
=20
and the thickness of each card the same and double the length, then the=20
volume also doubles. Doubling any single dimension causes the volume to=20
double, and in general multiplying a single dimension by any number will=20
multiply the entire volume bv that same number.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

</p><center>
<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"5" cellpadding=3D"0" width=3D"350">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"CENTER">
<table border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"3" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td><img src=3D"https://www.math.brown.edu/tbanchof/Beyond3d/Ima=
ges/chapter2/image10.jpg" width=3D"532" height=3D"203"></td></tr>
</tbody></table></td></tr>
<tr><td><small>A square-based pyramid is decomposed into four=20
rectangle-based pyramids having their top points over one corner.</small></=
td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</center>

<p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

This procedure enables us to obtain the volume of any pyramid of=20
rectangular base that has its top point directly over a corner of the=20
rectangle. We begin with a cube, having three times the, volume of an=20
off-center pyramid contained within it. We double the length of one of the=
=20
edges of the cube to form a rectangular prism, silnultaneously forming an=
=20
off-center pyramid with the same rectangular base. As we double the length=
=20
of the edge of the prism, its volume doubles. But all the slabs=20
approximating the volume of the off-center pyramid also double, so the=20
pyramid still has a volume one-third the volume of the prism. The basic=20
volume relationship still holds.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

What if the top point of the pyramid is located not over the corner but=20
over some other point of the rectangle? We can their divide the pyramid up=
=20
into four pyramids with the top point over one corner, and the volume of=20
each of these is one-third the area of the base multiplied by their common=
=20
height. Adding all of these contributions together shows that in general=20
the volume of a pyramid with a rectangular base is one-third the volume of=
=20
the rectangular prism with the same base and the same height.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"5" cellpadding=3D"0" width=3D"200" align=
=3D"LEFT">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"CENTER">
<table border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"3" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td><img src=3D"https://www.math.brown.edu/tbanchof/Beyond3d/Ima=
ges/chapter2/image11.jpg" width=3D"182" height=3D"147"></td></tr>
</tbody></table></td></tr>
<tr><td><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">
<small>Thin strips that fill a rectangle approximate the area of a=20
parallelogram.</small></p></td><td></td></tr>
</tbody></table>

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

It is also possible to deduce this result by applying Cavalieri's principle=
=20
for shear transformations, which again uses thick slices to approximate=20
areas and volumes: we can fill a parallelogram with the same set of rods=20
that fills a rectangle of the same base and height, and we can fill a=20
slanted box with the same pack of cards that fill a straight box. An=20
off-center pyramid can be approximated with the same collection of square=
=20
cards that approximate a centered one.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

The formulas for volumes of various kinds of square-based pyramids can be=
=20
modified to give formulas for pyramids formed by cutting off a corner of a=
=20
cube. The dimension of the space again appears in the denominator of the=20
formula, but in a new way. Cutting off one corner of a square produces a=20
triangle with half the area. Cutting off one corner of a cube produces a=20
pyramid with a triangular base. We can obtain this same triangular pyramid=
=20
by decomposing a square-based pyramid into four pieces. If we approximate=
=20
the square-based pyramid by a stack of square slabs, then the triangular=20
pyramid is approximated by a stack of triangular slabs each with half the=
=20
volume. It follows that the volume of the triangular pyramid is half the=20
volume of the square-based pyramid, or one-third the volume of the=20
triangle-based prism, therefore one-sixth the volume of the cube. The=20
four-dimensional volume of a corner hyperpyramid of a hypercube will be=20
one-fourth the volume of the triangular pyramid which is its=20
three-dimensional base, namely <sup>1</sup>/<sub>24</sub> the=20
four-dimensional volume of the hypercube. In general the=20
<i>n</i>-dimensional volume of a corner figure of an <i>n</i>-cube will be=
=20
1/<i>n</i>!, where n! stands for "<i>n</i> factorial," obtained by,=20
multiplying together the first n numbers.

</p><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">

</p><center>
<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"20" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td>
<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"5" cellpadding=3D"0" width=3D"350">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"CENTER">
<table border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"3" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td><img src=3D"https://www.math.brown.edu/tbanchof/Beyond3d/Ima=
ges/chapter2/image12.jpg" width=3D"322" height=3D"173"></td></tr>
</tbody></table></td></tr>
<tr><td><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">
<small>The same thin slabs approximate the volume of both a=20
centered square-based pyramid and a pyramid with the same base and its top=
=20
over one corner.</small></p></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</td><td>
<table border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"5" cellpadding=3D"0" width=3D"200">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"CENTER">
<table border=3D"1" cellspacing=3D"3" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tbody><tr><td><img src=3D"https://www.math.brown.edu/tbanchof/Beyond3d/Ima=
ges/chapter2/image13.jpg" width=3D"168" height=3D"173"></td></tr>
</tbody></table></td></tr>
<tr><td><p align=3D"JUSTIFY">
<small>Halving the slabs of a square-based pyramid approximates=20
a triangle-based pyramid.</small></p></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</center>


